[2] Vietnam: prevention and control
Date: Tue, 20 Mar 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: VietNam news agency [edited]
<http://vietnamnews.vnagency.com.vn/showarticle.php?num=02COM190307>

Vaccination programme controls bird flu effectively: FAO official
-----------------------------------------------------------------
The UN Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO)'s Laurence J Gleeson
was in Viet Nam last week to investigate the bird flu situation and spoke to
Viet Nam News about vaccination efforts.
Q. Why are you here, and what have been the results of your working
visits with Vietnamese officials?
A. The main reason for my coming this time has been to discuss the
vaccination programme.
The FAO has been involved with the Department of Animal Health for at
least 2 years in discussing vaccination strategy.
We are trying to move away from the concept of blanket vaccinations
twice a year and hope to bring a new programme into effect next year.
I have discussed some recommendations with technical people at the
Department of Animal Health and Deputy Minister of Agriculture and
Rural Development Bui Ba Bong.
Q. What recommendations have you made to the Vietnamese Government?
A. First, we must try to ensure a maximum level of protection of the
national flock during the winter months. A vaccination programme has to be
conducted nationally in October and November so there's good immunity
in the national flock during Tet when a lot of chickens are moved around.
Second, we hope to make vaccination of all poultry in the commercial
sector compulsory.
They must be vaccinated twice a year. Poultry for meat production
should be vaccinated at day one in the hatchery and again when they
are 3- or 4-weeks-old.
We must also have a special vaccination campaign for ducks and insist
that the duck population be vaccinated twice a year. FAO recommends that
vaccinations for ducks among small farmers should be free-of-charge
and supported by the Government, at least initially.
Vaccination of chickens in the commercial sector should be paid for
by the owners. The number of vaccinations should be reduced to once a year in
the backyard sector and concentrated in October and November. In
places where Government or local authorities think there may be more risk, they
can vaccinate an additional time during the year.
The Government needs a long-term plan to manage the vaccination
programme and needs to have a stronger information network in place about when
the disease is occurring so that responses can take place quickly.
Q. We've heard that a recent test from the Australian Animal Health
Laboratory revealed some minor mutations of the bird flu virus in Viet
Nam. What do you think about this?
A. I don't know the technical details so I can't comment on the
significance of it except to say that if there's a technically
consistent change in a number of viruses, then it would indicate some
slight genetic selection of the virus. We expect that where there is
a localised circulation of the virus, such as among ducks in the
south, there will be some genetic selection of the virus in that
environment. What is more serious is a significant change.
Q. Have there been any bird flu virus mutations in other countries?
A. Some people have made a comment that vaccination is more likely to
cause mutation. I would simply say no because there's no evidence.
Q. We did have some news material, such as a story entitled Egypt
Fears Bird Flu Mutation reported by Jenny Cuffe on the BBC on 14 Mar
2007, in which Dr Michael Osterholm, Director of the Centre for
Disease Control in the US [Dr. Michael Osterholm is Director of the
Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy of the University
of Minnesota in the USA - Mod.MPP] , pointed to the poor record of
poultry vaccinations in China and Viet Nam.
A. FAO disagrees that there has been a poor record of poultry
vaccinations in Viet Nam. Vaccination was used because the situation
was serious here.
We supported the Government and believe the use of vaccines has made
significant contributions to the control of the disease and the
reduction of public health risk in this country.
Q. He went on to say that vaccines may do more harm than good by
keeping birds from dying but allowing them to continue transmitting the virus.
A. Well, that's what vaccine is supposed to do. One reason for
vaccinating birds is to reduce virus circulation and the risk to
people but another
reason is to protect the production of birds which people rely on for
income. You can't have a poultry industry and can't control bird flu
if you don't control the virus.
The FAO is not pressing any country to launch a vaccination campaign.
We just provide technical support to ensure the vaccination
programmes are carried out effectively.
Q. Some have commented that the bird flu situation in Viet Nam is
less serious than in the last couple of years. What do you think?
A. The situation is probably not so serious in that most outbreaks
have occurred in ducks which were not vaccinated. We haven't had a situation in
which the disease was reported in vaccinated birds, which would be
very serious, and it has not crossed over to chickens to any large extent.
Q. What does the country need to do to eradicate the virus?
A. It's not endemic in any population but it could pop up at any time
because it can be re-introduced. To completely eliminate the virus
from the Mekong River Delta will be very challenging. Viet Nam over
the next 4 or 5 years should have a practical programme that
recognises when the disease is not present, the virus may still be
present and in circulation. If you relax control, the disease can come back.
Concentrate on eliminating the disease. Later, when there is no more
H5N1 virus circulating in the region, then start talking about
eradication of the virus.
--
