[4] Japan, Hodgson's hawk eagle
Date: Mon, 19 Mar 2007
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters alertnet [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/T81737.htm>

H5N1 kills rare eagle near Japan bird flu sites
-----------------------------------------------------
The H5N1 bird flu virus killed a rare species of eagle, captured
within 75 km (47 miles) of sites of 3 Japanese outbreaks of the virus
among poultry earlier this year, the environment ministry said on
Monday [19 Mar 2007].
Further tests are under way to see whether it is a highly pathogenic
strain of the H5N1 virus as well as genetic tests to determine its
roots, but the discovery has increased chances that the virus has
been carried to Japan by wild life [see comment].
_Spizaetus nipalensis orientalis_, often called Hodgson's hawk eagle,
is an endangered species in Japan. It does not migrate, and eats
small birds and animals. [Picture at
<http://www.princeton.edu/~vivekt/images/changeable-hawk-eagle.jpg>].
The ministry said the adult female bird was found sick but uninjured
on 4 Jan 2007 in Sagara village, Kumamoto prefecture, on Japan's
southernmost main island of Kyushu.
Japan later in the month confirmed its 1st outbreak of the H5N1 virus
since 2004 in neighbouring Miyazaki prefecture, the country's biggest
poultry-producing region.
Two other outbreaks have since hit Miyazaki and another occurred in
the western prefecture of Okayama.
While tests on whether the eagle suffered from lead poisoning proved
negative, a test for bird flu was positive followed by a later test
in which the H5N1 virus was isolated, the ministry said.
The ministry said it plans to resume surveillance of wild birds
around the site where the bird was captured.
The results of earlier tests for bird flu on samples of ducks and
other wild birds taken in areas immediately surrounding the 4
outbreaks had all been negative.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[According to Japan's official "immediate notification" to the OIE on
13 Jan 2007 regarding the confirmed reoccurrence of HPAI H5 (later
designated H5N1), after almost 3 years of absence, the event started
on 10 Jan 2007. See
<http://www.oie.int/wahid-prod/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=4522>.
In view of the fact that the incubation period of HPAI is regarded to
be 1 to 7 days, and that some time might have elapsed between the
initial infection and the appearance of clinically suspected cases
followed by sampling and testing, detection of an infected wild bird
on 4 Jan 2007 is not necessarily an indication of its role as the
pathogen introducer/infector but possibly as a sentinel of infection
in domestic fowl or another wild bird. As reported, this species
"does not migrate, and eats small birds and animals"; this might be a
supplementary evidence that the route of H5N1's (re)introduction to
Japan is still to be unveiled. - Mod. AS].
